const faqs = [
 { q: 'Do welders need flame-resistant clothing?', a: 'Yes. OSHA 29 CFR 1910.252 and AWS Z49.1 both require flame-resistant clothing for welding, cutting, and brazing. The base shirt and pants must be FR-rated — typically NFPA 2112-certified or recognized FR cotton. A leather jacket alone is not enough; the underlayer ignites if a leather seam fails.' },
 { q: 'NFPA 2112 vs FR cotton — what should a welder wear?', a: 'NFPA 2112 is the certified standard for flash-fire protection and is the conservative pick for any welding shop with safety-driven contracts. Heavy FR cotton (Carhartt FR, Bulwark Excel-FR) is acceptable under AWS Z49.1 for general welding. For oil/gas, refining, and process work, NFPA 2112 is required.' },
 { q: 'What FR shirt brands hold up for Vegas welders?', a: 'Bulwark Excel-FR ComforTouch SLU2 is the most-specified base shirt for Vegas welding and electrical crews — dual NFPA 70E + NFPA 2112 rating, 7 oz weight, breathes in summer heat. Carhartt FR Force is the next tier. Lapco and Tyndale also produce solid FR options at different price points.' },
 { q: 'Do I need a welding jacket if I\'m wearing FR?', a: 'For most stick, MIG, and TIG welding above 200A, yes. The leather jacket or sleeves protect against direct slag and spatter that an FR shirt resists but isn\'t designed to deflect. Heavy split-cowhide jackets from Black Stallion or Lincoln Electric are the standard. For light-duty TIG on thin material, FR alone is often enough.' },
 { q: 'Can welder uniforms be embroidered without losing the FR rating?', a: 'Yes — with Nomex (aramid) thread, applied by an FR-aware shop. Standard polyester embroidery thread melts and drips, which is worse than printing. NFPA 2112 garments retain certification when decorated with Nomex thread. Plastisol screen printing on FR is generally not approved by garment manufacturers.' },
