 <h2 class="mb-8 font-heading text-3xl font-extrabold uppercase leading-tight tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
 Welder uniforms for Vegas welding shops and contractors.
 </h2>

 <div class="space-y-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-ash">
 <p>
 A welder uniform is a layered protection system, not a single garment. The base layer — FR-rated shirt and pants — handles flash fire and arc events. The over-layer — leather jacket or sleeves — handles direct slag, spatter, and high-amperage stick work where the FR base alone isn't designed to deflect. Together they meet the requirements of <a href="https://www.osha.gov/laws-regs/regulations/standardnumber/1910/1910.252" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500" rel="noopener" target="_blank">OSHA 1910.252</a> and AWS Z49.1, the two standards that define welder PPE in the U.S.
 </p>
 <p>
 For Vegas welders, the base shirt question usually comes down to NFPA 2112 versus heavy FR cotton. NFPA 2112 is the certified standard for flash-fire protection — the conservative spec for any shop bidding on oil/gas, refining, process, or safety-driven commercial contracts. Bulwark Excel-FR ComforTouch SLU2 is the most-specified pick for Vegas crews because it carries the dual NFPA 70E and NFPA 2112 rating in a 7 oz weight that breathes in summer heat. Carhartt FR Force is the next tier. For general fab and lighter-duty welding under AWS Z49.1, heavy FR cotton from Carhartt FR or Lapco is acceptable.
 </p>
 <p>
 The leather decision is about heat input. Stick and high-amperage MIG (above 200A) generate enough slag and spatter that the FR shirt — designed to resist ignition, not deflect molten metal — needs a leather over-layer to handle the direct hit. Black Stallion and Lincoln Electric jackets are the standard; leather sleeves are a common compromise for summer work where a full jacket runs too hot. TIG on thin material often runs FR-only.
 </p>
 <p>
 Decoration is the part most shops get wrong. Standard polyester embroidery thread melts and drips on FR garments — a worse outcome than not decorating at all. We use Nomex (aramid) thread on every Bulwark, Carhartt FR, and Lapco garment we decorate, and we document the thread spec on the certification sheet that ships with every order. This is the document your safety officer needs in the binder when an inspector arrives.
 </p>
 <p>
 For deeper reads, see our <a href="/blog/welder-uniforms-las-vegas-buyer-guide/" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500">welder uniforms buyer's guide</a>, the <a href="/blog/welder-uniforms-fr-shirts-las-vegas/" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500">welder FR shirts deep-dive</a>, and the <a href="/blog/nfpa-2112-fr-coveralls-buyer-guide/" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500">NFPA 2112 FR coveralls guide</a>.
 </p>
